To check if all approvers with `summaryid = tracking.summaryid` are not null, and then update the `summarytrans` table with column `status` set to 2, you can use the following code:

```csharp
// Check if all approvers are not null
bool allApproversNotNull = await _dbContext.MaterialTransactionTrackings
    .Where(ts => ts.MaterialTransferSummary == tracking.MaterialTransferSummary)
    .AllAsync(ts => !string.IsNullOrEmpty(ts.Approver));

if (allApproversNotNull)
{
    // Update summarytrans table with status = 2
    var summary = await _dbContext.MaterialSummaryTrans
        .FirstOrDefaultAsync(st => st.SummaryId == tracking.MaterialTransferSummary);

    if (summary != null)
    {
        summary.Status = 2;
        await _dbContext.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

In this code, we first use the `AllAsync` method to check if all approvers with `summaryid = tracking.summaryid` are not null. If this condition is satisfied, we retrieve the `summary` record from the `summarytrans` table using `FirstOrDefaultAsync` and update its `Status` property to 2. Finally, we save the changes to the database using `SaveChangesAsync`.

To update the `status` column to 1 if the very first data, ordered by sequence, has a non-null `approver`, you can modify the code as follows:

```csharp
// Check if the very first data has a non-null approver
bool isFirstApproverNotNull = await _dbContext.MaterialTransactionTrackings
    .Where(ts => ts.MaterialTransferSummary == tracking.MaterialTransferSummary)
    .OrderBy(ts => ts.RouteDetailNavigation.Sequence)
    .Select(ts => !string.IsNullOrEmpty(ts.Approver))
    .FirstOrDefaultAsync();

if (isFirstApproverNotNull)
{
    // Update summarytrans table with status = 1
    var summary = await _dbContext.MaterialSummaryTrans
        .FirstOrDefaultAsync(st => st.SummaryId == tracking.MaterialTransferSummary);

    if (summary != null)
    {
        summary.Status = 1;
        await _dbContext.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

In this code, we added an `OrderBy` clause to order the data by `Sequence` and used `FirstOrDefaultAsync` to retrieve only the very first data.

Then, we used the `Select` method to project the `!string.IsNullOrEmpty(ts.Approver)` condition for each record and obtained the value of the very first data.

If the `isFirstApproverNotNull` condition is true, we update the `Status` property of the `summary` record to 1 and save the changes to the database.

